    thinking: "**Analyzing the Current Setup**\n\nI\'m currently reviewing the `package.json` file. It seems a basic React setup is in place, with Express and tsx. The current scripts are a Vite-based dev server and a Vite build command.\n\n\n**Defining the Architectural Approach**\n\nI\'ve decided to proceed with a client-only web app architecture, based on the user\'s instructions. A fast React frontend with simulated modes and ESP32 HTTP integration is the goal. I\'m also planning to incorporate a `server.ts` handler for local testing and potential proxying. The emphasis is on local control and a seamless development experience for the user.\n\n\n**Refining the Architectural Scope**\n\nI\'m now clarifying the architectural scope. Initially, I was leaning towards a client-only architecture with a local server for dev. However, given the user\'s intent to serve the app from the ESP32 itself, I realize the Express backend is only for local development. The final product is a pure client-side React SPA, compiled into static HTML/CSS/JS for flashing onto the ESP32. I\'m building a development environment with `server.ts` to mock the ESP32\'s capabilities, along with `dist/index.html` for deployment.\n\n\n**Establishing Data Structures**\n\nI\'m now focusing on establishing data structures. I need to declare standard types for pins, devices (nodes), settings, and logs to maintain clean separation of concerns. I\'m also planning a `src/data.ts` to keep static data like mock ESP32 pin definitions. I\'m aiming for modularity and maintainability from the outset.\n\n**Designing UI Components**\n\nMy focus has shifted to designing UI components. I\'m envisioning a `src/components/ESP32Visualizer.tsx`, which will render a vector layout of the ESP32 DevKit, showing the pinout and highlighted active pins. I also have `src/components/PinController.tsx` for pin control and `src/components/NodeMonitor.tsx` for network visualization, allowing cross-control of other nodes.\n\n**Implementing Code Export**\n\nI\'m working on the `src/components/FirmwareExporter.tsx` module. I am generating modular C++ code for Arduino IDE with ESP32 WebServer, complete and heavily commented. I\'m making sure it\'s well structured to meet user needs.\n\n\n**Adding New Features**\n\nI am now adding new features. I\'ve designed a log console (`src/components/LogConsole.tsx`) that mimics ESP32 serial output for enhanced debugging. I am also implementing an AI Assistant (`src/components/AiAssistant.tsx`) using `@google/genai` to help users customize automation tasks and generate C++ code snippets. These are great additions to make the experience more intuitive.\n\n\n"
